text: If you are in SF and have any porch you can be on, let’s all come outside on NYE at midnight with some kind of twinkling lights. Let’s make our own light shows across the city and celebrate even at a distance that 2021 will hopefully be better and that vaccines are rolling out

I told him I just get high on life and when other people are also this way it is contagious. If I could go back in time, I would tell him we are all children inside still and that joy and sense of wonder is there underneath trauma. It’s in all of us. I love you Tony.

One of the things Tony marveled about me, is that I can have a *lot* of fun sober. We’d often get really goofy and he’d double and triple check if I had anything to drink. I rarely and almost never do. He asked me lots of questions about how I did it (get goofy)

Also, one thing the article gets wrong is that some people he hired 2x their best salary, he didn’t see them when they showed up. So, they were not all enablers. Some were there to do real work. That’s too broad of a brush and not accurate.

This all doesn’t negate the work he did to try and find and teach “happiness”, but it does point out that those seeking it, often don’t have it yet. If you know someone seeking it, it’s already inside of them. There’s no external way to get it.

text: Tony was highly functional with his drinking. He would even ask me, “can you tell I’ve had anything to drink? Is there anything wrong with me? No? Then don’t worry”.

Unfortunately, he also hired a doctor who apparently told him whatever he wants to hear. Perhaps he also had some friends who did the same, but the choice was still his and I’m not sure what could have been done about any of it.

I told him it won’t be that easy, but Tony seemed to bend other things to his will. I still, decided to express my worry to him whenever I saw him and his responses were similar. He was hell-bent on self-medication.

text: I’ve expressed my worry to him many times about his drinking and the last time we spoke about it, he held my hands and said “Cyan, I have a doctor and he checks me often and he says I’m fine. If he ever tells me I’m not fine, I will quit in that moment”.

I feel that this was respectful of two simultaneous truths. Tony was an amazingly beautiful and wonderful person and also deeply complicated. He was a genius and like a lot of geniuses, wounded. He used the wrong tools to cope. https://t.co/I60zp94eQQ

text: RT @Dangerangel: @cyantist I used to work in homeless services. If you see a homeless person wearing BRAND NEW NIKES - think of Tony Hsieh.…
@jhong If I could hug you right now I would. I’m so heart broken. He made a dent in the universe.
I’m going to miss him so much. He’s everywhere, so I will see reminders of him every day. I’ll try to channel some of his wisdom when I need help. You are so so so loved Tony.

Tony wasn’t afraid to be “weird” and embraced randomness. He tried different things and lived many lives in one honestly too short of a life. He explored and saw so much and had a list for adventure. I’ll try to find videos and photos to post tomorrow.

Tony gave the most amazing back rubs. He’d ask you if you wanted one and then work on your back for a long time and not in a haphazard way. He would shed light on his current musings while doing it and then he’d run off to whatever was next in his world.

Once, I saw Tony give a presentation about Zappos early on and he was so great on stage, which was something I found odd for someone who was shy. He told me his secret and he freed me from my speaking anxiety. He didn’t practice and made up what he’d talk about right before.

text: Tony loved connecting dots. He was a master at figuring out which people should know each other and why.
Tony was service oriented and if I was carrying anything, he would grab it out of my hands and carry it. He would lecture me about having too many things, but he’d carry it anyway.
Tony loved many people and he loved to tell me about those he loved. The way he described people and what he saw in them was delightful.
RT @OnwardsAndrew: Generous. Loving. Friend. He delivered happiness for so many of us. The countless shared stories of his character helps…

People may not know this but Tony was shy and he came up with games he’d play to help break through this shyness in order to be in public with strangers. He always loved to tell me about his little social experiments.
RT @pmarca: "No matter what your past has been, you have a spotless future." -- Tony Hsieh, RIP
Tony messaged me out of the blue on days when he sensed I needed a little encouragement. His spidey sense was amazing. He always knew what to say.

text: I’ve been on Twitter 12 years and I was just reminded how things like this have algorithms and UI that’s designed to suck us back in again. Unfortunately, Twitter has moved into a deadly sin category of rage. It isn’t healthy for us to be exposed to so much of it or dish it.

I’m going to try to figure out how I can balance this. Maybe I can only use it in my desktop when I return and maybe only a set amount of time a day. I don’t the answers yet, but I do know, like many others, current events hurt and I believe we are all hurting in some way.

And I think historically I’ve added to others lives here as well. It means a lot to me that sometimes I speak for those who feel they can’t. However, I’ve reached a point where I need to step away for a while. For my family and for myself and probably for my friends too.

Unfortunately, so much disinformation will be spread about this and some people won’t question it and it will be designed to drive people even further apart. Don’t let it!!

As for what else happened, I think we need a lot more information. There needs to be more witnesses and footage as this isn’t enough to determine anything. For example, the shooter is a security guard for a news station.

I think we will find out this isn’t as simple as Trump vs antifa. A bunch of white guys are surrounding a guy who’s wearing a BGM shirt and one pulls out a baton - for what? I see this person as standing their ground against being beat up or worse.

entity.description: Don't be ridiculous! When it comes to Internet videos run amok, however, the more zany, unbelievable and downright dangerous the clips are, the greater the chance they'll be shown on this series. It features amateur viral videos being critiqued by MTV personality Rob Dyrdek ("Rob Dyrdek's Fantasy Factory"), who knows a thing or two about pushing the envelope from his pro skateboarding days. With commentary from Sterling "Steelo" Brim and Chanel (the rapping receptionist from "Fantasy Factory"), Dyrdek breaks down the clips by putting them in such categories as "Hot Mess," "Worst Case Scenario," "Redneck Good Times" and "What Happened Last Night." It's sure to be seriously ridiculous.

These fights would often become physical with my mother escalating things. I have a vivid memory of my mother cornering my father and trying to pour freshly brewed hot coffee all over him. I also sadly have a memory of my step-father’s brother hitting my mother while she was pregnant with my brother with a frying pan. My mother could say some scathing things without raising her voice ever and cut you down, but words escalating to violence seemed so odd to me. I took to hiding in my room more.

text: I don’t engage with profile photos or bios but rather ideas. I won’t look you up before I talk to you. I refuse to do that offline as well because I like to judge every single human being by character, not snippets. We aren’t a few lines of text on Twitter. None of us.

But man, I have to say I love the people who reach out to me and say “you are wrong, please see this perspective”. It’s classy, smart and will get my respect 100% of the time and I will *always* listen.

I will not wilt like a flower. You can’t cancel any human being. You can call me trash all you want, but I know my self worth and who I am. I love everyone and I believe people are fundamentally good. Even some people message me hatred and I send them love and then we talk.

But if you feel better calling me names, threatening me, etc., then you’ll get to have fun with it once but I hope you examine that anger and hatred and the ultimate cost of it long term. There’s so much more to be gained by making bridges than burning them down.

Which I find a shame because there’s an opportunity here to reach out to me and talk and friendships and bonds could be made. I get that people are hurting, but hurting back is never the answer. A simple “you are wrong” is powerful enough if that’s what you believe.

I get it - they have a lot more to lose than I do. I’m going to keep being me and be the best me I can be. The only cost to this is that I once would engage with anyone about anything but now if you can’t be civil, you are forever out of my life. Period.
For every single person spewing vitriol at me, there are 10 or more people sending me love, advice, perspectives and being civil, but sadly a lot in private because of fear of mobs well, being mobs.

The issue is how police handle resisting of arrest and if it is applied fairly. Apparently it isn’t. How would you handle resisting and someone arming themselves?

I’m going to go back to helping prison reform and shut up because that’s one of the core issues here. Mass-incarceration of men and the destruction of families is what leads us long term to these destructive ends.
@RogerLRomanII Ok ;-)
@dbeyer123 People shouldn’t be executed period. But you also can’t go around grabbing knives and resisting warrants for domestic abuse / sexual assault. Or is that ok now?

@dbeyer123 I never said he was asking to be executed. I said he should have stopped walking and he shouldn’t have reached for a knife. And yes there’s love in trying to think of all aspects and people involved. Including whoever called 911
@xtraordnrymchn @ArlanWasHere You are wrong. So wrong.
@ArlanWasHere I also respect you deeply Arlan. Thank you for taking the time.
@sometechnews_ And you follow me why?
@jarin And we should disagree. How do we get to the right answers if we can even discuss them? Thank you for this.

@ekp @ArlanWasHere I don’t think we can also normalize DV and I’m afraid that’s going to happen. Black women in particular are disproportionately abused because of so many reasons I can’t start to get into. So I see this as finally something is being done to protect them, but somehow not?

@ekp @ArlanWasHere I appreciate that you recognize what I am actually trying to accomplish here. I absolutely do not think we should shoot people in the back but I also don’t know what to do if someone resisted arrest for DV, withstands non-lethal measures, walks away and then arms himself.

@OneBandwagonFan @ArlanWasHere I also think he should have stopped walking and should not have grabbed a knife. Those two things and he might not be injured now. I don’t want him injured and I don’t want police shooting people in the back. People conflate these things because I’m trying to see perspectives.

@OneBandwagonFan @ArlanWasHere And I’m pro demilitarized policing. It’s fucking ridiculous. I’m alarmed when someone, in this case, close to this man called 911 for help and that he had a warrant for domestic sexual assault. Who is she is and what happened there. Do I think he should be shot? No.

@OneBandwagonFan @ArlanWasHere I am talking about my own home. Nobody should have take away Breona’s sense of safety. What happened to her is devastating and murder. She had the right to defend her home and well being as do I.

@techladyallison @ArlanWasHere His own mother blew me *away*, yet the press only covers the very first part of her talk. She even prays for police officers and their families. She doesn’t want houses to burn. She wants justice. I too want justice but I also don’t want to assume what is in anyone’s heart.

@techladyallison @ArlanWasHere He also reached for something that turned out to be a knife. Why would he do that? I know the fear of if you’ll live through a police altercation is real, so why would you do that? All I ask is that we try to figure out what happened and find love somehow.

Women die at the hands of domestic abusers every day. A man’s fists can be lethal. We beg police to protect women from this abuse, often asking “why was something not done? Where were the cops? Why don’t they care.” When they do something, finally, the police are villains.

@meklitgebre Yes we should be able to do that always. I don’t think we should shoot unless it is a last resort. If Dylan had this past history and he was brandishing the gun, it would have been completely justifiable to shoot.

@bk2thfutre No it shouldn’t be
@Scandalous If they are reaching for a gun, do you wait until they turn around and shoot you? Is your reaction time that good?
@CarlosPero @BuddyGoldenDog We are literally political pawns on all sides of the equation

@CarlosPero @BuddyGoldenDog They won’t sadly. It does happen and it isn’t the thing that politicians and media outlets can use to sow division and make us all hate one another. Blake’s mother has it right. We must find love for one another and peace.

@MichaelKogan14 @BuddyGoldenDog Maybe your criminals are more polite? We definitely have systemic problems here and a race war that didn’t end because we mass incarcerate people for the dumbest things. Our justice system has broken families. I get it.
@CarlosPero @BuddyGoldenDog That’s all they can do. Right now this is a normal day that usually goes without incident and the person goes with them. The officer also deserves a fair trial.
@CarlosPero @BuddyGoldenDog What if nobody signs up for this job anymore? What if the officer was black and did the same thing?
@jarin They are bringing him in so his guilt can be determined. Does his victim not deserve justice?
@CarlosPero @BuddyGoldenDog We will find out. He’s alive and he may sue them and all of this will come to light. This is something that needs to go to court.

@BuddyGoldenDog You know that happens a lot with all walks of life and these officers have to walk into this every single day. I don’t like excessive use of force. What happened to Floyd in my opinion was vastly different than this. Breona? Murder.

@BuddyGoldenDog If you try to arrest someone and they wrestle you on the ground, you then tase them and they then go to their car and reach for what could be the firearm that was there *before*, you might feel your life is now in danger. If he turned around and shot the cop?
@ianb How do you know that? They have his plates

I’m not sure what we are supposed to do if we are sexually assaulted and people can’t be brought in to face justice for their crimes? Do they just ask nicely? It doesn’t work that way. Shooting should always be a last resort, but he wasn’t just casually walking to his car.

He resisted arrest in the past and caused bodily harm to an officer. Had to be taken down by a k9. He’s had a firearm in his car in the past and was reaching to a similar spot when he opened the door after he was tazed and they tried to subdue him with non-lethal force.

I am deeply saddened by the shooting of Blake, but we should try to remember that each case has its own individual circumstances. This man was wanted for sexual assault and domestic abuse, as well as he had a record of brandishing a firearm in bars while intoxicated.

text: @Andrewmd5 How can you say someone wasn’t harmed? If I can’t sleep anymore or have PTSD, was I harmed? I don’t think that’s up for you to decide.
Theirs is too, but outside of my home and in theirs which they can also protect. It’s pretty simple. Don’t hurt people and don’t steal their shit. Don’t invade homes and lives won’t be lost.

And I’m not going to question my privilege when it happens either. Nope. If you are in my home and you shouldn’t be, then your life is in immediate danger. It isn’t about what you’ll take, it isn’t about what is replaceable or not. My safety and my life is valuable.

Life is precious. Both mine and yours. However, if someone is invading my home, I will kill them. I don’t want to. It doesn’t bring me joy. But nobody is taking away my sense of safety. Sorry. I’m not going to question how the system has failed them, they will just be super dead.

@NathanLands @Andrewmd5 @arrington The loss of feeling safe is a very real and damaging thing that is difficult to ever repair. I agree completely.

@Andrewmd5 Your take came off as insensitive because of timing. It also seems like you felt he was privileged for speaking about his own experience. I think if you saw him as also just a human being navigating the world you two would like each other a lot.

@Andrewmd5 Sure. I don’t agree with mass incarceration and I’m positive that Daniel doesn’t either. I’m asking you to show compassion to him as well. He was just violated. Not once but four times. This time was incredibly serious and I won’t get into the details, but a group was involved.

@Andrewmd5 Daniel had someone blowtorch his door open and he has neighbors with small children. For him he knows he can replace things. The issue is how does he feel safe sleeping or living his life? That’s what was really robbed.

@Andrewmd5 I’m trying to help give perspective here. I know what you went through. I also did things I regret to survive, but I also know they were wrong. You are right we should help the youth more but the timing for advocating that isn’t when someone just felt their safety eroded.

@Andrewmd5 Or maybe that person worked months to get what they have and their own personal mental health suffers because they were just robbed when they just got on top of their life. Mental health isn’t replaceable either.

@Andrewmd5 Also not all stuff is replaceable. Some things have really deep meaning for people. While it had no meaning to you, doesn’t mean that for everyone else. For example something passed down generations.

@Andrewmd5 You can’t know a persons life or intentions if they are violating your space. You just can’t and like you said, life is precious. If I feel my life is in danger I will shoot the person trying to take mine or anyone else’s.

@Andrewmd5 When we drive around in cars we don’t hit each other because we care about self-preservation. If you fear you’ll be shot entering a home that isn’t yours, you are unlikely to enter it. It is a deterrent. People don’t want to shoot someone, trust me.

@Andrewmd5 A different perspective: The feeling of safety can’t be replaced either. Once you’ve had a violation of your safety you can’t get that back either. For some it isn’t about stuff, it’s about violation. Also it’s about not knowing if a person is going to take your life or rape you

urls.title: Beverly (16)
urls.description: Listen now (12 min) | She's a punk punk, a punk rockerPunk punk, a punk rockerPunk punk, a punk rocker. - Ramones The Ramones tape I found on the ground? I must have played that until it suffered the fate of most tapes - eaten by the tape deck. My mother didn’t mind the Ramones, but she freaked out over my dual interest in hip-hop, and by that, I mean The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air. She would go on and on about how it was a gateway album to the NWA. I hadn’t heard of NWA until she ranted about them, so naturally, I had to check them out. A friend at school had a tape that they let me listen to at lunchtime. I loved the irreverence of the music as it felt like a different kind of punk rock. Like the Ramones, there was a tension you could feel in the music, and it was beyond the lyrics, it was built into the energy of each song. If you accept the invitation, songs can tell you things even if you erase the lyrics.

text: Everyone, and I mean everyone who’s an adult is wearing their trauma, including you. It starts young and it’s mostly caused by ourselves and our own inner narratives. Cast it all away and you’ll find that child underneath is still there.
If you look around you, there are invitations everywhere. Where do they go? Why don’t you find out?
Sometimes the magic you are searching for is right in front of you. Reframe every negative thought and it will be interesting what suddenly becomes interesting.
What we all want more than anything in the world is the magic of childhood back. We build up walls and armor and cosplay as “adults”. We forget to play. Never forget to play.
